/*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*\
  sprayDryer02_residence_sweep
  ============================

  The DRYING CURVE of the sprayDryer01 sugar dryer, obtained by sweeping
  the chamber HEIGHT --- the design question "how tall must the chamber
  be to dry the powder?".  This is the credo at work: chamberHeight is a
  HARDWARE parameter (streams IN -> unit OP with parameters -> streams
  OUT); the RESIDENCE TIME (= height / particle fall velocity) and the
  final moisture X_final are both RESULTS read off the powder.  Nothing
  here is a spec.

  The ~58 µm droplets (d32 = 58.1 µm here, vs 60.4 µm in sprayDryer01
  --- this case uses a case-local sucrose.dat) dry sub-second, and they
  fall slowly, so the window that shows all three regimes is a SHORT
  chamber (~0.01-0.1 m, i.e. residence ~0.01-0.15 s):

      * constant-rate period   X falls linearly from X_in (1.5) to the
                               critical Xc (0.15);
      * falling-rate period    (Lewis) X decays exponentially from Xc
                               toward the GAB equilibrium Xe (0.014);
      * equilibrium plateau    X_final = Xe once residence >> drying time.

  X_critical and X_equilibrium are emitted as flat reference lines so the
  knee (at Xc) and the floor (at Xe) are visible on the plot.

  PEDAGOGICAL POINT: a real spray dryer runs with seconds of residence,
  i.e. far to the RIGHT on this curve --- on the equilibrium plateau.  So
  the residual moisture of fine-droplet drying is set by the sorption
  isotherm and the air humidity, NOT by the residence time.  The
  residence time only matters for coarse droplets or very short chambers
  (the left part of this curve).
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

application   choupoSolve;
description   "Spray dryer: chamber-height sweep -> the drying curve (residence = L/v; constant + falling rate -> equilibrium)";

verbosity     2;
